    <td bgcolor="#ffffff" valign="top" width="70%"> <h3>Best Practices</h3>
      <p>Accept no substitutes! Anyone with a web site can <i>claim</i> to provide 
        eLearning. How does one separate the real stuff from the bogus? Legitimate 
        eLearning is more likely to:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Focus on the needs of the learner, not the trainer or institution</li>
        <li>Take advantage of the net: real-time, 24/7, anywhere, anytime</li>
        <li>Bring people together to collaborate and learn together</li>
        <li>Personalize, often by combining "learning objects" on the 
          fly</li>
        <li>Offer more than one learning method, e.g. virtual classroom and simulation 
          and self-paced instruction</li>
        <li>Incorporate administrative functions such as registration, payment 
          and charge-backs, monitoring learner progress, testing, and maintaining 
          records</li>
      </ul>
